Thera Bank Personal Loan Campaign¶

This case is about a bank (Thera Bank) whose management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors). A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio with a minimal budget.

Domain¶

Banking

Table of contents¶

Introduction¶

The data that has been provided consists of banking information for 5000 customers of Thera Bank. The goal of this project is to help the retail marketing department to devise new campaigns for their liability customers.

The dataset contains data on 5000 customers. The data include customer demographic information (age, income, etc.), the customer's relationship with the bank (mortgage, securities account, etc.), and the customer response to the last personal loan campaign (Personal Loan). Among these 5000 customers, only 480 (= 9.6%) accepted the personal loan that was offered to them in the earlier campaign.

The classification goal is to predict the likelihood of a liability customer buying personal loans.

Observation:¶
  • There are no outright null values.
  • Age: Average age of a customer with the bank, is 45
  • Experience: Experience column has minimum of -3. This does not look right. This could be because of invalid data entry. This will need to be fixed.
  • ZIP Code: Takes numerical value, but not quantitative. Eg: Sum of two zip codes is not meaningful.
  • Mortgage: Atleast 50% of the customers dont have a mortgage with the bank.
  • Securities Account: Atleast 75% of the customers dont have a Securities Account with the bank.
  • CD Account: Atleast 75% of the customers dont have a CD Account with the bank.
  • Online: 50% of the customers have Online access to their account with the bank.
  • CreditCard: 50% of the customer dont have a credit card with the bank.
  • Some of the categorical columns are showing up as numerical. We will convert them.

    not_taken_personal_loan = cust_df[cust_df["Personal Loan"] == 0][var]

num_plots = len(count_plot_columns)
total_cols = 3
total_rows = 2
fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows=total_rows, ncols=total_cols, figsize=(20, 10))
for i, var in enumerate(count_plot_columns):
    row = i//total_cols
    pos = i % total_cols
    ax = sns.countplot(cust_df[var], edgecolor="black", ax=axs[row][pos])
    total = len(cust_df[var])
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.0f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total)
        x = p.get_x() + 0.4
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x,y), size = 12, ha = 'center', va = 'center', xytext = (0, 10), textcoords = 'offset points')
    ax.set_title("Distribution of {0}".format(var))
axs[1,2].set_axis_off()
fig.tight_layout(pad=4.5)
plt.show();

    for p in ax.patches:

        x = p.get_x() + 0.2
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x,y), size = 12, ha = 'center', va = 'center', xytext = (0, 10), textcoords = 'offset points')
    ax.set_title("Distribution of {0} with Personal Loan".format(var))
axs[1,2].set_axis_off()
fig.tight_layout(pad=4.5)
plt.show();
Observation¶
  • Education - Of the customers: 42% are Undergraduates, 28% are Graduates and 30% have Advanced/Professional Education Levels
  • Securities Account - 90% of the customers dont have a Securities Account with the bank.
  • CD Account - 94% of the customers dont have a CD Account with the bank.
  • Online - 60% of the customers use Internet Banking Facilities
  • CreditCard - 71% of the customers dont have a Credit Card with this bank.

When compared along with Personal Loan information:

  • Education - 4% of customer who are Graduates or with Advanced/Professional Education Levels accepted the Personal Loan. So people with higher education level seem to accept Personal Loans more.
  • Securities Account - 8% of customers without Securities Account accepted the Personal Loan
  • CD Account - 7% of customers without a CD Account accepted the Personal Loan
  • Online - 6% of customers using Internet Banking Facilities accepted the Personal Loan
  • CreditCard - 7% of customers without Credit Card from this bank, accepted the Personal Loan

mask = np.zeros_like(correlation)
mask[np.triu_indices_from(mask, 1)] = True
sns.heatmap(correlation, ax=axes_corr,  linewidths=.5, cbar_kws={"shrink": .5}, cmap=cmap, vmin=-1, annot=True, fmt=".2f", mask=mask)

Observation from the correlation map¶

# Lets prepare the data for the model

# Drop the ID column that is just a 1-1 mapping
loan_df = cust_df.drop(columns="ID")

# Experience shows a min of (-3). This could be incorrect data.
print("Number of customers with invalid years of experience : {0}".format(cust_df[cust_df["Experience"] < 0].shape[0]))

cust_with_valid_experience = cust_df[cust_df["Experience"] >= 0]
median_valid_experience = cust_with_valid_experience["Experience"].median()

print("Replacing invalid experience with Median             : {0}".format(median_valid_experience))

# Replace invalid experience with Median (20)
cust_df.loc[cust_df["Experience"] < 0, "Experience"] = median_valid_experience

print("")
print("Customer Experience -- Describe")
print(cust_df.Experience.describe())


loan_df['ZIP Code'] = loan_df['ZIP Code'].astype('category')
loan_df['Education'] = loan_df['Education'].astype('category') # Takes values 1-3
loan_df['Personal Loan'] = loan_df['Personal Loan'].astype('category') # Takes 1 or 0
loan_df['Securities Account'] = loan_df['Securities Account'].astype('category') # Takes 1 or 0
loan_df['CD Account'] = loan_df['CD Account'].astype('category') # Takes 1 or 0
loan_df['Online'] = loan_df['Online'].astype('category') # Takes 1 or 0
loan_df['CreditCard'] = loan_df['CreditCard'].astype('category') # Takes 1 or 0

experiments = {}

all_columns = loan_df.columns.difference(["Personal Loan"])
Y = loan_df[["Personal Loan"]]

# EXP1: First we will test with all columns

def split_data(description, df_to_use):
    print("Splitting data for                         : {0}".format(description))
    X = pd.get_dummies(df_to_use, drop_first=True)
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.30, random_state=1)
    print("Original Personal Loan Accepted Values     : {0} ({1:0.2f}%)".format(len(loan_df.loc[loan_df['Personal Loan'] == 1]), (len(loan_df.loc[loan_df['Personal Loan'] == 1])/len(loan_df.index)) * 100))
    print("Original Personal Loan Not Accepted Values : {0} ({1:0.2f}%)".format(len(loan_df.loc[loan_df['Personal Loan'] == 0]), (len(loan_df.loc[loan_df['Personal Loan'] == 0])/len(loan_df.index)) * 100))
    print("")
    print("Training Personal Loan Accepted Values     : {0} ({1:0.2f}%)".format(len(y_train[y_train['Personal Loan'] == 1]), (len(y_train[y_train['Personal Loan'] == 1])/len(y_train)) * 100))
    print("Training Personal Loan Not Accepted Values : {0} ({1:0.2f}%)".format(len(y_train[y_train['Personal Loan'] == 0]), (len(y_train[y_train['Personal Loan'] == 0])/len(y_train)) * 100))
    print("")
    print("Test Personal Loan Accepted Values         : {0} ({1:0.2f}%)".format(len(y_test[y_test['Personal Loan'] == 1]), (len(y_test[y_test['Personal Loan'] == 1])/len(y_test)) * 100))
    print("Test Personal Loan Not Accepted Values     : {0} ({1:0.2f}%)".format(len(y_test[y_test['Personal Loan'] == 0]), (len(y_test[y_test['Personal Loan'] == 0])/len(y_test)) * 100))
    return (X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test)

def create_confusion_matrix(axs, row, pos, description, actual, predicted, training_accuracy, testing_accuracy, precision, recall, f1_score, roc_auc_score):
    if axs.ndim > 1:
        axis_heat_map = axs[row][pos]
    else:
        axis_heat_map = axs[pos]

    labels = ["TN","FP","FN","TP"]
    cf = confusion_matrix( actual, predicted)
    group_labels = ["{}\n\n".format(value) for value in labels]
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}\n\n".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()]
    group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()/np.sum(cf)]
    box_labels = [f"{v1}{v2}{v3}".strip() for v1, v2, v3 in zip(group_labels,group_counts,group_percentages)]
    box_labels = np.asarray(box_labels).reshape(cf.shape[0],cf.shape[1])

    stats_text = "\n\nAccuracy(Train) = {:0.3f}\nAccuracy(Test) = {:0.3f}\nPrecision = {:0.3f}\nRecall = {:0.3f}\nF1 Score = {:0.3f}\nROC AUC Score = {:0.3f}\n".format(training_accuracy, testing_accuracy, precision, recall, f1_score, roc_auc_score)
    
    heatmap = sns.heatmap(cf, annot=box_labels, annot_kws={"size": 14}, linewidths=0.5, linecolor='w', fmt="", cmap="Oranges", cbar=False, xticklabels="auto", yticklabels="auto", ax=axis_heat_map, square=True)
    axis_heat_map.set_title(description, fontsize=14)
    axis_heat_map.set_ylabel("Actual", fontsize=14)
    axis_heat_map.set_xlabel("Predicted" + stats_text, fontsize=14)
    axis_heat_map.set_xticklabels(axis_heat_map.get_xticklabels(), rotation = 45, fontsize = 10)
    axis_heat_map.set_yticklabels(axis_heat_map.get_yticklabels(), rotation = 25, fontsize = 10)
    
    return_list = [value for value in cf.flatten()]
    return return_list


def log_regression(axs, row, pos, description, df_to_use, log_reg_params):
    print("******************************** " + description + " ******************************************************")
    print("")
    logreg = LogisticRegression(**log_reg_params)
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = split_data(description, df_to_use)

    logreg.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_predict = logreg.predict(X_test)
    training_accuracy = logreg.score(X_train,y_train)
    testing_accuracy = logreg.score(X_test, y_test)
    precision = precision_score(y_test,y_predict)
    recall = recall_score(y_test,y_predict)
    f1score = f1_score(y_test,y_predict)
    rocscore = roc_auc_score(y_test,y_predict)
    
    cf_list = create_confusion_matrix(axs, row, pos, description, y_test, y_predict, training_accuracy, testing_accuracy, precision, recall, f1score, rocscore)
    
    return_list = [training_accuracy, testing_accuracy, precision, recall, f1score, rocscore]
    return_list = ["{:0.3f}".format(value) for value in return_list]
    return_list = cf_list + return_list
    return_list.insert(0, description)
    
    print("")
    print("********************************************************************************************************")


    return [X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test, logreg, y_predict, return_list]

Discussion on Confusion Matrix Terms¶

  • True Positive (TP) (Predicted = 1, Actual = 1)

    Predict that the customer will take the Personal Loan, and they actually took it

  • False Positive (FP) (Predicted = 1, Actual = 0)

    Predict that the customer will take the Personal Loan, but they did not take it

  • True Negative (TN) (Predicted = 0, Actual = 0)

    Predict that the customer will not take the Personal Loan, and they did not take it.

  • False Negative (FN) (Predicted = 0, Actual = 1)

    Predict that the customer will not take the Personal Loan, but they actually took it. This is where the bank will loose money on missed oppotunity.

Important Metric¶

If the bank fails to reach out to a customer who will take the Personal Loan, the customer continues being a depositor and the bank has to keep paying them interest. So bank has to take measure to ensure more people take the Personal Loan, so that the bank can get more interest.

Since the bank stands to loose money if the FN goes up, our goal should then be to reduce FN. Which is achieved by improving Recall (Total Positive Rate)

So for any further performance improvement, Recall will be used a measure

Reasoning Consideration¶

The following hyper paramters were modified to get better performance

  • C : Inverse of regularization strength - Regularization is applied to penalize the increasing of magnitude of the parameter values to reduce overfitting. Especially when we have a lot of independent variables but sparse data, then the model tries to overfit. To reduce this, penalty is applied. C captures this information. So basically if there is very little data and too many parameters, then there is a possibility of overfitting. So we should make sure we have sufficiently large dataset.

  • class_weight: Balances the weight assigned to the classes. Setting to "balanced" makes sure, the value of "y" is used to auto adjust the weights.

  • solver: The algorithm used in the optimization problem. For small datasets, liblinear is a good choice, whereas sag and saga are faster for large ones.newton-cg, lbfgs, sag and saga handle L2 or no penalty. liblinear and saga also handle L1 penalty

Ideally, to get a good fit and good performance

  • We should have sufficiently large dataset with balanced classification. Here we had only 9.6% of customers who take Personal Loan.
  • Based on the size of dataset, we need to vary the solver, C and class_weight to see what combination gives better performance for the metric of choice.
  • Identifying the metric that matters the most is important. Is it Recall or Precision or both (F1Score). Based on this the parameters can be tweaked and tried again, until we get better performance

6. Give Business understanding of your model¶

  • The bank is obligated to giving out interest to those customers who are depositors.
  • If the bank does nothing, it has to keep paying interest.
  • By having a customer take a Personal Loan, the bank stands to gain interest for the loan, from those customers.
  • So with more number of customers taking Personal Loan, the bank will get more interest and hence save money that it pays out in interest to depositors.

So with the model, the bank aims to identify those customers who have the potential of taking Personal Loan

From the confusion matrix, we understand the following:

  • True Positive (TP) (Predicted = 1, Actual = 1)

    Predict that the customer will take the Personal Loan, and they actually took it

  • False Positive (FP) (Predicted = 1, Actual = 0)

    Predict that the customer will take the Personal Loan, but they did not take it

  • True Negative (TN) (Predicted = 0, Actual = 0)

    Predict that the customer will not take the Personal Loan, and they did not take it.

  • False Negative (FN) (Predicted = 0, Actual = 1)

    Predict that the customer will not take the Personal Loan, but they actually took it. This is where the bank will loose money on missed oppotunity.

For every customer who potentially would take a loan, and the bank missed reaching out to them, the bank looses on interest paid. This is captured by FN (False Negative)

So the goal is to have a low FN. This translates to higher Recall

In terms of FP, bank will reach out to customer who will not take the loan, but thats ok. Because its not adding more loss to the bank. (May be a loss in terms of marketing budget and time). So Precision is not so important in this case.
